```javascript
function isPrime(num) {
  if (num < 2) return false; // 0 and 1 are not considered prime
  for (let I = 2; I <= Math.sqrt(num); i++) {
    if (num % I === 0) return false;
  }
  return true;
}

function checkPrimes(arr) {
  for (let num of arr) {
    if (num > 1 && isPrime(num)) {
      console.log(`${num} is a prime number.`);
    }
  }
}

// Example usage:
const numbers = [3, 7, 12, 17, 23];
checkPrimes(numbers); // Output: 3 is a prime number. 17 is a prime number. 23 is a prime number.
```

The `checkPrimes` function iterates over each number in the input array (`arr`) and checks if it's greater than 1 (to exclude 0 and 1), and if it's a prime number using `isPrime` function. If a prime number is found, it prints it to the console. Note that we pass each number in the array to the `isPrime` function to check its primality.

The `isPrime` function checks if a given number `num` is prime by looping through all numbers from 2 to the square root of `num` (inclusive) and returns `false` if any divider is found, otherwise returns `true`.

With this implementation, the function returns `undefined` if no prime number is found in the array. Here's the complete code with comments:

```javascript
function isPrime(num) {
  // Check if num is less than 2 (not a prime number)
  if (num < 2) return false;
  // Loop through all numbers from 2 to the square root of num
  for (let I = 2; I <= Math.sqrt(num); i++) {
    // If num is divisible by any number, return false (not prime)
    if (num % I === 0) return false;
  }
  // If no factor found, num is prime
  return true;
}

function checkPrimes(arr) {
  // Check each number in the input array
  for (let num of arr) {
    // Check if num is greater than 1 (exclude 0 and 1)
    if (num > 1 && isPrime(num)) {
      // If num is prime, print it to the console
      console.log(`${num} is a prime number.`);
    }
  }
}

// Example usage:
const numbers = [3, 7, 12, 17, 23];
checkPrimes(numbers); // Output: 3 is a prime number. 17 is a prime number. 23 is a prime number.
```

Now, when you call `checkPrimes(numbers)` with an array of 5 numbers, it will check each number and print the prime numbers to the console.

